Conic Combination Interpretations – Example



Example (Basis Change Illustration)


3x1+x2−2x3+x4=2,x1+3x2−x4=2.
\begin{align}
3x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3 + x_4 &= 2, \\
x_1 + 3x_2 - x_4 &= 2.
\end{align}





Suppose we start with 𝐚1\bm{a}_1 and 𝐚2\bm{a}_2 as the initial basis and select 𝐚3\bm{a}_3 as the incoming column. Then 

𝐁=(3113),𝐁−1=(3818−1838),𝐚‾0=𝐁−1𝐛=(1212),𝐚‾3=𝐁−1𝐚3=(−34−14).
\begin{equation}
\bm{B} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 & 1 \\ 1 & 3 \end{pmatrix}, \quad \bm{B}^{-1} =
\begin{pmatrix} \frac{3}{8} & \frac{1}{8} \\ -\frac{1}{8} & \frac{3}{8}
\end{pmatrix}, \quad \bar{\bm{a}}_0 = \bm{B}^{-1}\bm{b} = \begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2} \end{pmatrix}, \quad \bar{\bm{a}}_3 =
\bm{B}^{-1}\bm{a}_3 = \begin{pmatrix} -\frac{3}{4} \\ -\frac{1}{4}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}


From Equation 5, ε=2\varepsilon = 2 and 𝐚2\bm{a}_2 is the outgoing column so that the new basis is formed by 𝐚1\bm{a}_1 and 𝐚3\bm{a}_3. 
Now, suppose we start with 𝐚1\bm{a}_1 and 𝐚3\bm{a}_3 as the initial basis and select 𝐚4\bm{a}_4 as the incoming column. Then

𝐁=(31−20),𝐁−1=(01−1232),𝐚‾0=𝐁−1𝐛=(22),𝐚‾4=𝐁−1𝐚4=(−1−2).
\begin{equation}
\bm{B} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 & 1 \\ -2 & 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad \bm{B}^{-1} =
\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -\frac{1}{2} & \frac{3}{2}
\end{pmatrix}, \quad \bar{\bm{a}}_0 = \bm{B}^{-1}\bm{b} = \begin{pmatrix}
2 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}, \quad \bar{\bm{a}}_4 =
\bm{B}^{-1}\bm{a}_4 = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ -2
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}


Since the entries of the incoming column 𝐚‾4\bar{\bm{a}}_4 are all negative, ε\varepsilon in Equation 5 can go to ∞\infty, indicating that the feasible region is unbounded.
